# Project Development Rules
You are an expert Full-stack developer. Your goal is to maintain high-quality code and UI consistency.

## Tech Stack & Consistency
- Stack: React (Vite) + TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui.
- Icons: Lucide React.
- Data: TanStack Query + Supabase.
- IMPORTANT: Prioritize modularity, reusability, and clean prop-types.
- IMPORTANT: Always prioritize using the knowledge from indexed @Docs (Supabase, Tailwind, shadcn) to ensure up-to-date implementation.
- MOCK DATA: If a database schema is missing, use clean TypeScript interfaces to define expected data structures. Always prefer descriptive naming conventions.

## Database & Schema Methodology (IMPORTANT)
- ABSENT SCHEMA: If no `@db-schema.md` exists or is empty, DO NOT guess table names or column types. Instead, prompt the user: "Please provide the Supabase schema or table definitions for this feature."
- PLACEHOLDERS: Use descriptive placeholder names (e.g., 'table_name', 'column_name') in comments where SQL/Supabase logic is required, ensuring easy replacement later.
- RLS ENUMS: When writing RLS policies that check a custom enum role (e.g., `app_role`), always cast string literals explicitly: `'admin'::app_role`. A plain `'admin'` string will cause a type mismatch error at runtime.
- RLS FUNCTION PREFIX: Always call custom functions with the `public.` schema prefix inside storage policies: `public.has_role(auth.uid(), 'admin'::app_role)`. Storage policies run in the `storage` schema context and will not resolve unqualified function names.

## Supabase Auth & Storage (CRITICAL)
- API KEY: Always use the Supabase **anon JWT** (`eyJ...`) as `VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`. Never use a platform publishable key (e.g., `sb_publishable_...`) — it will silently fail for all authenticated requests.
- STORAGE UPLOAD: Never use `upsert: true` in `supabase.storage.upload()`. This triggers an UPDATE path that requires a separate `USING` RLS policy. Use a plain `upload()` with `upsert: false` (the default) so only the INSERT `WITH CHECK` policy is evaluated.
- STORAGE BUCKET STRUCTURE: Organize files into subfolders by content type (e.g., `products/`, `articles/`, `branding/`) within a single bucket. This keeps RLS policies simple and bucket management clean.
- See `ai-utils/supabase-patterns.md` for a full list of known pitfalls.

## Prompt Ops & Consistency (CRITICAL)
- PROMPT FOLDER: Always check the `/ai-utils` folder for the general UI style guide (`@ui-style.md`) before creating new UI elements or features.
- UI CONSISTENCY: When asked to build a new page or component, look for `@ui-style.md` to ensure the design matches the original aesthetic (Premium style, shadow-sm, specific Hebrew typography).
- VISUAL ASSETS: Use the status indicators and emojis defined in `@visual-assets.md` for consistency in dashboards and lists.
- USAGE PATTERN: When the user says "Add [Feature]", analyze existing prompt files to replicate the same Zod validation and RTL alignment patterns.
- Ensure all new components follow the Hebrew/RTL rules and Typography defined in this project to avoid visual regressions.

## Hebrew & RTL (CRITICAL)
- The app is in Hebrew. Use `dir="rtl"` on main layouts.
- Use Tailwind LOGICAL properties exclusively to ensure bidirectional support:
  - `ms-*` instead of `ml-*`
  - `me-*` instead of `mr-*`
  - `ps-*` instead of `pl-*`
  - `pe-*` instead of `pr-*`
- TYPOGRAPHY: Use modern Hebrew fonts like 'Heebo' or 'Assistant' for a professional look. Ensure font weights are consistent (400 for body, 600/700 for headings).
- All user-facing text must be in Hebrew.

## Standards
- Prioritize modularity and reusability in all components and utilities.
- Use Arrow Functions for components.
- No 'any' type in TypeScript.
- Always check `@/components/ui` before creating new UI elements.
- DOCUMENTATION: For every meaningful change in the project (new features, structural changes, stack updates), update BOTH `README.md` (English) and `README_he.md` (Hebrew) to keep them in sync.
- DATA QUERIES: Always filter queries to the current user's data. Never fetch unbounded rows that belong to other users. Use RLS policies as the server-side safety net, and always add client-side `.eq()` filters as an additional layer.

## Data Integrity (CRITICAL)
- JSONB INSERT: When inserting numeric values into JSONB columns, always cast explicitly: `'30'::jsonb` not `'30'`. JavaScript reads uncast values as the string `"30"` and `Number('"30"')` returns `NaN`, silently breaking any logic that depends on the value.
- OWNER_ID: Every table with an `owner_id NOT NULL` column must include `owner_id: user.id` in every INSERT. Missing it causes a DB error even when RLS would otherwise allow the operation.
- FK BEFORE INSERT: Never store an entity name directly in a child table when a FK relationship exists. Always lookup or insert the parent entity first, then reference its `id` as the foreign key.
- ENUM/CHECK ALIGNMENT: Before adding a new option to a UI select/dropdown, verify it exactly matches the DB `CHECK` constraint values. A value not in the constraint will cause the insert to fail silently or with a generic error.

## UI & UX Standards (CRITICAL)
- NO NATIVE DIALOGS: Never use `window.confirm()` or `window.prompt()`. Replace with shadcn `AlertDialog` for confirmations and inline input fields for data entry.
- NO FAKE SUCCESS: Never show `toast.success` before a Supabase operation completes and returns without error. Always `await` the result, check the `error` field, and only then trigger success feedback.
- NO HARDCODED AMOUNTS: Never render currency amounts as `` `$${x.toLocaleString()}` ``. Always use a formatting function or hook that respects the user's preferred currency/locale.
- UNUSED CODE: After any refactor, remove unused variables and imports immediately. Dead `const sym = ...` declarations and unused icon imports cause linter noise and obscure real issues.
